==> Why terraform init? 
terraform init = Prepare the workspace. Before Terraform can create AWS resources, it needs to:
✅ Download the required providers (like AWS). ✅ Set up the backend (where state is stored). 
✅ Download any referenced modules. ✅ Prepare the current directory so plan and apply can run.
It does not create AWS resources.

==> 
terraform/environments/dev/main.tf = need to write
module "vpc" {
  source = "../../modules/vpc"

  project_name          = var.project_name
  environment           = var.environment
  vpc_cidr              = var.vpc_cidr
  availability_zones    = var.availability_zones
  public_subnet_cidrs   = var.public_subnet_cidrs
  private_subnet_cidrs  = var.private_subnet_cidrs
  database_subnet_cidrs = var.database_subnet_cidrs
}
Why? Think of it like this:

modules/vpc/main.tf       = Machine (knows how to build a VPC).
environments/dev/main.tf  = Power switch (tells Terraform: "Use this machine now").
Right now your power switch is OFF because environments/dev/main.tf is empty.

So the flow should be:

modules/vpc/main.tf
        ↓
environments/dev/main.tf  ← Calls the module
        ↓
terraform plan
        ↓
terraform apply
        ↓
AWS creates VPC, Subnets, IGW, NAT Gateway...

This is the only change you need before continuing.

==> What's happening?

dev/main.tf is calling the VPC module.
But dev/variables.tf doesn't declare the variables.
So Terraform stops with "undeclared input variable".
